The paper deals with the application of Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) for prostate zonal segmentation in Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) datasets. This falls under the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of Squeeze-and-Excitation (SE) blocks, which are a type of attention mechanism, to improve the performance of the CNN. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper deals with medical imaging, which could place it under the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates the generalization ability of the CNN-based architectures, which could suggest that it belongs to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
